<Name>John Hatch< /Name>< Time>
1622680074485< /Time>
< Rating>
4< /Rating>
<review>The Venice Canals are a short walk from Venice Beach, and provide a unique location for a relaxing stroll. Parking can be a bit tricky, but there is a lot on the corner of South Venice Blvd. and Pacific Ave. The lot was full so we ended up parking at a 2-hr. meter on Washington Blvd. and walking over. This gave us plenty of time to walk around. The kids enjoyed going up and over the arch bridges that span the canal, and even put their hands up like it was a roller-coaster. We saw ducks, other birds, and butterflies. The walkways were a bit narrow, but we still managed with a stroller. Bikes are not allowed, and the general consensus is no boating for visitors. Home owners have their boats, but there are no rentals. After doing some reading, it seems possible to bring your own, but as this is a residential area it is probably best to choose another area for that. I‚Äôd hate for it to become an issue with the residents, and ruin it for everyone. Enjoy the out of the country feel, and peaceful vibes while walking the canals instead. I do want to go back to check out Linnie Canal Park, which has a playground.<//review>< pictures>

<userid>100502370616087630944</userid><user_name>Paul Smith<//user_name>< Time>
1617205800623<//Time>
<Rate>5< /Rate>< Review>
AMAZING!!! I've been going to Venice Beach since I was a very young child and only after 4 decades did I even hear a rumor that it once had canals like Venice, Italy. I thought it was an interesting story and when my sister had a Zoom birthday party for my nephew from my cousins place at the canals, it didn't really sink in until the next day. She called my cousin, and we're there the following day.
On the way there, I anticipated going somewhere far away from anywhere familiar but no. In fact, only blocks away from a very familiar Venice Beach was a hidden world more beautiful than anything place I've seen in Los Angeles, in a very long time. I had the best day I've had in a very long time, also. Mostly from the company but the beautiful backdrop of the canals totally enhanced the experience. It feels like I was let in on a great secret world within my hometown and I feel special. However, the traffic reminds me I am still in LA but it is, in fact, worth seeing regardless.</Review>

<text>We visited here shortly before Christmas 2020. There is plenty of free parking available on Venice Boulevard. After that it is a short walk to the canals. Dell Avenue is a good entry point. Thereafter, you can walk up and down the canals across various bridges. For the Christmas festive period, there are plenty of lights on the bridges. And many of the houses along the canal are nicely decorated and lit up. All in all, a very pleasant experience.<//text><Pictures>None</Pictures><Response>None<//Response><Gmap_id>0x80c2baa2bf5a7289:0x96e7291be897f918</Gmap_id></record>

<UserId.>109916502486366067204</UserId.>< username>
See LA in a Day< /username>
<Date>1619554402967< /Date>< Rate>
5</Rate>
< Text>
There are few housing developments with as much history and appeal as this little canal area.
This section of canals used to be known as the "New Amsterdam Canals" but were eventually officially named after their investors and architects - Howland, Sherman, and Clark. Like so much of Venice, the were stunning when they opened and suffered from decades of deterioration. In the 90's, the canals were renovated, bringing them up to the condition we see them in today. If you've never been, go grab an $18 smoothie (-_-) at Erewhon and walk along the sidewalks and bridges that criss-cross the area!< /Text>

<Response>None</Response><Text>This place was really neat. I thought you could ride in a little gondola or boat around the canals, but that's for the homeowners. There is no place to ride any around. All the houses have little docks and boats to ride around the canals. If you walk the canal route correct, you can walk the entire thing in one loop without back tracking. The houses on the canals are amazing! The backyards are unique also. We really enjoyed looking at the yards and houses as well as the gorgeous canals. It's a little over 2 miles to walk the entire route without back tracking. It's a nice and quiet walk. You can take your dogs, just make sure to clean up after them. The residents have signs asking to clean up after pets. No bike riding is allowed on the walkway.<//Text>< Name>
Stacey Mitchell</Name>

<review>gorgeous area, was nice to see everyone abiding the covid/ mask regulations, I just wish the area passed the canals where all the shops, fancy restaurants, and food places were located were less crowded. I also hate the air in LA/Venice but it's just how it is unfortunately, so its very rare I can even go there these days, I could handle it a little better before all of my auto immune issues became so severe, but these days I can barely handle it in small doses. Thankfully the mask helped prevent me from getting as sick from the pollution as I usually do. I am still going to give 5 stars though because the state of the awesome historical Canal wasn't affected by the previously mentioned things I stated above, it was still gorgeous and gives off an amazing vibe. There's lots of really cool sea birds, I even saw one that looked very unusual compared to all of the ducks, cranes, and egrets. this guy had a very unusual shape and feet compared to the rest, he stayed alone sitting on this one boat for over an hour straight (he was there when I walked through the canal, and was there later when I walked by it to go back to the car!) several others took pictures of him aside from myself.< /review><time>1613639072204< /time><GmapID>0x80c2baa2bf5a7289:0x96e7291be897f918< /GmapID>< username>

< Review>
It‚Äôs one of the most charming spots in the city. It has so many beautiful houses along the walk, which is really unique. It‚Äôs also really close to the beach, so if you find a spot to park your car by the beginning of the canal, you‚Äôll be able to have a nice walk around Venice.< /Review>

< review>
The place is worth visiting I think only once not more. The canal itself is not that clean. This looks like a little venice. You may walk along the canals for about an hour . There is nothing exta intetesting just houses and the canals and some little boats which are not for renting.<//review>

I went on a late weekday afternoon and it was just beautiful! Even on a overcast day in Venice. < Text>
Depending on what time you go. I've been there both daytime and night time. Parking is free on the street but depending what time you go. Might take a while to find parking. It is a great place to go with a date. Or just by yourself. I went couple nights ago. There was very few people walking there at night. Spend easy 30 mins here by walking around.< /Text>

<user_name>Liseli Martin<//user_name>< text>
What a wonderful discovery. There are paths that you walk and all sorts of nooks and crannies and little side streets. The houses are part of the scenery and are really beautiful. The people who live here seem to be amused by the tourists but are kind anyway. There are so many bridges and it looks like you can take a row boat out as well. Take lots of water with you. Try to keep track of where you are it seems easy to get ost there. You can either exit Venice beach side or the street.</text>

< Review>
I love this part of LA! You can just walk and stroll along the water for a while and completely forget that you are in the middle of an extremely busy city. Each front yard is very well manicured and the water is surprisingly clear and clean, free of sewage smell.  I highly recommend stopping by, it is a must-do!< /Review>

< Review>
If you go to Vegas and you end up at the Venetian... And you happen to be they're with somebody special... Then after you visit Madame Tussauds Wax Museum you have to take a ride in an authentic Venetian gondola.  It's about $80 for a couple but totally worth the experience.  Tray elegant!!! And the gondola drivers are hilarious.  If you don't make it to Venice in your lifetime this will be the closest you'll get to the real thing.  Super cool!<//Review>

< text>
One of the iconic spots of LA. You can call it a hidden gem as most of em miss out while visit Venice Beach. Hardly at a walking distance from the beach, this place is meant for photography enthusiasts.

Though I won‚Äôt suggest going there or towards the end of summers as the canal will be dry.
It‚Äôs a nice place to take your date or best half for an evening walk. Always calm and nice.</text>

[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPaJgxA1AF4y1GmoM1GxfbTIDHVFe3CE9PghV6P=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOCgdxT-H37rc5O68_NAcnuMNI3XcVtzCJu2y_C=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pictures>

None<//Response>
<text>The canals are roughly bounded by Eastern Court on the east, Court A on the south, Strongs Drive on the west, and Court E on the north. There are four east-west canals (Carroll Canal, Linnie Canal, Howland Canal, and Sherman Canal) and two north-south canals (Eastern Canal and Grand Canal). The lit canals with gondoliers and arched bridges drew widespread publicity and helped sell lots in the development.

By the 1920s already well into the age of the automobile as cars were quickly and increasingly gaining popularity the canals were viewed by many as outdated, and as a result a number of canals of the original network were filled in 1929 to make room for paved roads. By 1940, the remaining canals had fallen into disrepair, and the sidewalks were condemned by the city.[2] The canal district remained in poor condition for more than 40 years, as numerous proposals to renovate the canals failed due to lack of funding, environmental concerns, and disputes as to who should bear the financial responsibility. The canals were finally renovated in 1992, with the canals being drained and new sidewalks and walls being built. The canals re-opened in 1993 and have become a desirable and expensive residential section of the city.< /text><UserId.>103208015192776997537< /UserId.><Name>Mercedes Lamperti<//Name><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP_y7LHHVCkh5pcFAzLciTj8F6qVS41vt9DR6dP=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNX-cY1cxMP3B5Yy4URhR72seLqmadYLkmV2Sfp=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': <time>1571371838321</time><Name>Youri Labrie< /Name>< review>
Except the presence of canals it doesnt look like Venice in Italy. Nevertheless the canals and surrounding houses are beautiful and a place of tranquility, especially when there are no other tourist (groups) around. If you walk from Venice beach through 25th Ave you will cross a mini version of the San Francisco Lombard street. It's a crooked street with a tiny park. Since it was near Halloween when I was there, the owners decorated the area pretty nice. Please be respectful and keep the noise down as this is a neighbourhood and you're walking through the residents backyard. I think it's a matter of time before a resident start a nice little backyard lunchroom.<//review>

< review>
A nice walk along the streets which goes parallel to the canals. The houses around are beautiful. When you are around surely stop by and spend at least 30 minutes walking along the peaceful canals.
Finding a parking could be difficult. Otherwise just get here stress free and enjoy the walk.
This place also reminded me of many hollywood movies and TV series which were shot here.< /review>

< Review>
Truly one of the terrific hidden places along the west side. The Venice boardwalk is oh yeah crowded Beachside seeing lots of multi trade shops this is just a couple yards away to the East and is a little quiet Paradise off the main streets located just east of Pacific between Venice Boulevard and Washington Boulevard is just a lovely way to walk around and look at the sites much of this quaint Cottages have been Mansion eyes but there are still several than his places and some of the new ones are interesting you can see every form of architect for residential affluence all within a 5-minute straw. Lots of very well fed Ducks here</Review>

<Rate>5< /Rate>< text>
What a wonderful discovery. There are paths that you walk and all sorts of nooks and crannies and little side streets. The houses are part of the scenery and are really beautiful. The people who live here seem to be amused by the tourists but are kind anyway. There are so many bridges and it looks like you can take a row boat out as well. Take lots of water with you. Try to keep track of where you are it seems easy to get ost there. You can either exit Venice beach side or the street.<//text>

<rate>4< /rate>< text>
This is a must see place when visiting LA / Venice beach area. It's only a short walk from the main beach. There use to be 7 canals which were created to mimic the canals in Venice. Since that time though, some of the canals have been filled in for housing, which only leaves a couple left to be viewed. Great to walk around and snap those tourist pictures. I would recommend to anyone who is in the area.<//text>

< text>
Beautiful place in the heart of the city and yet very quiet and peaceful , this little corner of paradise full of trees and colorful flowers has given us a breath of fresh air. The comings and goings between canals, bridges, everything was magnificent. Surrounded by palm trees and magnificent houses, these canals are a must in Venice.You will feel like in a movie. <Response>None< /Response>< review>
Amazing place, amazing views for an amazing stroll. If you have not been to Venice or have been to, this place will make or bring back memories. Beautiful small roads each one leading to a canal with beautiful colorful houses on either sides makes this a perfect destination for family, friends or dates on a warm sunny day or breezy evening.
The snaps attached speak for themselves.
A place of must visit for anyone traveling to LA.</review>

< text>
If you are in LA, make the effort to go to Venice and check out the canals. It's like another world, nothing else in LA, heck, probably the US compares to this little bit of paradise. The houses are all beautiful, and the perfect canals that wind around are just breathtaking.< /text>

< GmapID>

<user>101117091515134890849< /user>< Text>
A backdrop for many shows set in the area (especially recognizable from "Californication") these canals are connected by a set of sidewalks and bridges. It's a very beautiful walk, and there are all sorts of cool examples of local architecture. Speaking of locals, they are very friendly too. It's not unusual to run into someone just enjoying a beautiful day in Southern California on their porch. A great diversion if you have already hit the beach and boardwalk. Just remember that people live here, so be polite, clean, and please don't trespass onto their property.< /Text>

<Gmap_id>0x80c2baa2bf5a7289:0x96e7291be897f918<//Gmap_id><Review>Beautiful place to walk around and take in the pretty sites. I think the water is low during the off season but still very attractive area. A lot of the houses have wonderful flowers growing along the fronts of their homes. The canals are such that they're layed out in a grid pattern. It's nice to walk down one way, cross over a bridge and then walk back up the other side. Then you can repeat that process again for each of the remaining fingers.

NOTE: No motorized scooters allowed...You must walk this area since the houses sit so close to the water, the sidewalks are very narrow!

I recommend it if you like quiet walks with manicured gardens.< /Review><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMNWGKE2VNn3XTZxCCNarxxcrsNTRhefCMNd5cx=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMgXECR-hrORrxpjQL-RLBU-fVbhxO6ouvD_yjR=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNIa4eaaI5BhgxWrY3L82BVvNxNH4ZsiFOSKW2X=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNrWYGt2QTCkD8V7p-8jhw9NfM_X_8lI9r-j5Zn=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMS8tZ4JM9T5OpU5qgn2BXlOK6YQMlrvLRVl8g2=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN4KNIGkfHreBUMpugw71ygHOIsz1o49xQNWRr3=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM-V6HdUfxLCDOxlH7HOF3ZBr9eBtAhjD_Q8pRN=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pictures>< user_id>

This place is absolutely breathtaking, with unique houses surrounding the canals. A great place to go for a walk on a sunny day, you'll enjoy the great effort people have spent on their houses and some of them generous enough to leave great views for the passerbys. Also very close to Venice Beach.</Review>

<rating>5< /rating><text>What an amazing place this would be to live. So beautiful. So peaceful. And yet so close to the ocean and the action of the Venice Beach boardwalk only without the lowlifes and the noise intrusion. This has now bumped Coronado in San Diego as the place I would most like to live in the USA if I won the lottery (or if Bitcoin skyrockets as high as some think). Of course living in a place so desirable comes with a steep price tag.  Even the less impressive, run down bungalows go for millions according to a realtor I stopped and chatted with about the area. I hope the people who live here appreciate how fortunate they are to live in such a great place. Definitely visit if coming to Venice Beach and you appreciate quality real estate and architecture.</text>< pictures>

<Name>Natalie Romaniuk</Name>< date>
1553890398064<//date>
< rating>
5<//rating>
< text>
Great view of the man made canals. Can walk along the small sidewalk, cross bridges and take pictures. Some hotels/airbnb's no doubt around this area. Scenic and a site to see if you're visiting the city. We parked by Abbot Kinney (by Inteligensia coffee) and walked to the canals. Probably the best decision because parking can be tricky.

Update: We went to the Venice Canals in Feb 2019, and they were looking pretty weak. There isn't a lot of water and the canals seemed to have dried up, leaving some boats and canoes on soil (see pic). I was shocked to see this.<//text>

< Review>
It's very nice, very pretty. Price of buying home in that area is attainable if you can earn $300k a year.  If you want the same with a lot smaller cost of living, but Italy inspired canals where the price of homes range from $250k on up, then Cape Coral,  Florida is the place. With all the man made canals and affordable living (approximately 30% cheaper to live in than San Diego,  California). Cape Coral has more canals than Italy, about 400 miles worth.<//Review>

<Time>1571371838321< /Time><Rate>5<//Rate><Text>Except the presence of canals it doesnt look like Venice in Italy. Nevertheless the canals and surrounding houses are beautiful and a place of tranquility, especially when there are no other tourist (groups) around. If you walk from Venice beach through 25th Ave you will cross a mini version of the San Francisco Lombard street. It's a crooked street with a tiny park. Since it was near Halloween when I was there, the owners decorated the area pretty nice. Please be respectful and keep the noise down as this is a neighbourhood and you're walking through the residents backyard. I think it's a matter of time before a resident start a nice little backyard lunchroom.< /Text><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMhqjgtLgPpnESrkSkFteJlPYF-vXCOWe4tRHKH=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipML9eA0MTLEqiJjqByIy5DlMRt4gjicF5rIKogA=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pictures><Response>None</Response><gmapID>0x80c2baa2bf5a7289:0x96e7291be897f918<//gmapID></record></dataset><record>

Each of the houses located here is immensely different from the next, from small cozy cottages to full on modernist pieces. There's not really much of a crowd, so enjoy a quite walk through the neighborhood and across the bridges, look for the occasional waterfowl in the quiet water. < Review>
Had the good fortune to stay on Venice Beach canals last weekend. Walking them was so enjoyable - each is charming in its own way, and the spring blooming everywhere made it extra delightful. It can get noisy off Grand Canal, but others are quiet. Do this if in VB.</Review>

<Rating>5<//Rating>< text>
Great for evening walk right before sunset. There are plenty of people walking their pets and the pathways are quite narrow so be aware of cross traffic and if you're afraid of pets. Lots of places to take really cool pictures. Best time is around twilight so the lighting for pictures and weather is that much better. There is plenty of paid parking around as well.</text>

<review>I'm a native Venetian, although I moved away about 15 years ago. I recently went to visit old friends and took a walk by the "new" Canals. Actually it didn't even look like the same neighborhood. I was quite impressed how nicely the Canals were restored. Nice ambiance. New and renovated homes and the landscaping gives it lots of appeal. Only one thing I noticed typical of Venice was the mucky algae water in certain places. But, hey, that's Venice. It fits. Never thought I'd ever be saying anything good about Venice...but yes, here it is... the Canals are probably the nicest part of Venice! But don't even think of living there unless you have megabucks!</review>< Gmap_id>

< Response>
None</Response>
< Review>
This somewhat historic part of LA is a great place to stroll around on a summer afternoon. I say somewhat historic because the canals go back to the original Venice in America development of Abbot Kinney. The tiny Beach cottages that were originally built here have all but disappeared, to be replaced by a number of architectural curiosities and some decent houses. The canals themselves have been cleaned up, and walking along the narrow sidewalks you will see the houses, very elaborate gardens, a few rowboats and lots of dogs.<//Review>

<userid>100325759258300018969<//userid>< name>
Catry Lai< /name>
<date>1532472966977</date><rate>5<//rate>< Review>
Personally, I loved it there. Its design is similar to Venice in Italy, where there are canals for people to travel through. Interestingly, this is actually a neighborhood, where most homes have their own mini dock and a kayak or boat. All the houses are colorful and unique. I was there on a Wednesday morning, around 10 a.m., and it was very peaceful. It's not "fun" or "interesting", but for people who wants a slower pace amidst their packed schedule, I absolutely recommend taking a walk there!<//Review>

< review>
Great place for a morning stroll. I come here time to time to shoot sunrise and there's many perspectives to capture! This place is great when you have a colorful sunrise or sunset, but not so much during midday or overcast skies. It's a quiet neighborhood so please mind the people living here, but they're friendly. Parking is available just outside the canals in the morning. I recommend the lower west corner of the canal since that's the place to capture most of the palm trees in the scene.< /review>

<user_id>104428950806203714789< /user_id><username>Deborah Groening<//username><time>1560093723335< /time>< rating>
1</rating>
< Text>
People visiting the Canals need to understand that this isn‚Äôt a park, it is a residential area ‚Äî public, but not a party venue. Respect the people who live here who share this place with others. Keep your voices down, water carries voices. Do not trash it, do not loiter, do not ride bikes, skateboards, Segways, or electric scooters against traffic. We have ONE access road. We can‚Äôt see over the driving bridges. When folks go the wrong way, local drivers are terrified. When we leave our alleys, we are used to looking one way, since Dell Ave is one way. Don‚Äôt trash the Canals with bikes or scooters. Respect the wildlife who are also getting stressed by so many people and from the intense noise that pollutes our peace and tranquility. Eggs aren‚Äôt hatching. Ducks are almost non-existent. Don‚Äôt block the one-lane Dell Ave with your car to take some scenic shots. Walk in if you want to enjoy the views, but remember not to block Dell with your bikes or strollers at the bridges because it is busy with pedestrians who want to walk on either side of the road safely. Don‚Äôt stop the flow of traffic by parking or stopping at the Dell Ave bridges, it isn‚Äôt a scenic lookout spot.</Text>

<user_id>115694659138468382563<//user_id>< username>
Saad Rana<//username>
<time>1525500076261< /time><rate>5</rate>< Review>
Beautiful canal view in the historic district of Venice. Best place to visit on a weekend especially with family or a significant other. The canals themselves as well as the unique architecture of all surrounding houses makes this neighbourhood/tourist spot an amazing place to walk and relax. The serene setting of Venice canals make you forget the craziness of LA as a huge city. The best part is the proximity to Venice beach and a number of bars and restaurants right around the corner. I recommend entering the canals from the Washington Blvd entrance as the real views are from that side. I visit nearly every weekend to relax and destress.</Review>

< Name>
John Riles< /Name>
<Date>1558384150961< /Date><Rating>4< /Rating>< Review>
This is a really great place to meet diverse groups of people. Parking is not that bad if you are willing to pay. Less expensive parking can be found up the street. There are plenty of scooters and bikes for rent, if you don't want to walk. My only suggestion on that is don't use Uber or Jump scooters if you wwnt to ride on the boardwalk. They will not allow you to ride on the boardwalk. There are plenty of other scooter rentals that do. Have fun;-)< /Review>

<GmapID>0x80c2baa2bf5a7289:0x96e7291be897f918</GmapID></record></dataset><record>
<user_id>110740681117335561450</user_id>< name>
ChrisW<//name>
<time>1559177021286< /time><Rating>5</Rating>< text>
A true hidden gem. This tucked away little section of Venice is one of the most unique areas in the city. Beautiful homes line the only 6 remaining canals, and walking paths allow people to get up close and personal with the homes and the waterways. The canals do go up and down with the tide. Try to time your visit with high tide, it'll make a world of difference for your photos and general experience. Grab a coffee and head over in the morning (9-11am) to avoid larger crowds, but the canals never have the same level of craziness that you find by the beach. It's a perfect spot to walk around and talk with a significant other. Please try to be considerate of the neighborhood though. Peoples homes are right by the walking paths. So try your best not to peer into someone's home or be super loud in the early/late hours.</text>

Josh Lower< /user_name>
<Resp>None< /Resp>< review>
What a cool area. The mixture of houses and landscaping with water and bridges comes together beautifully.  Really enjoyed just walking around and taking pictures. It was like a subculture. Families along the path had their homes and yards open to onlookers.  Houses ranged from colorful and bright, to sleek and sheek. Take some time, walk around and take it all in. Definitely visit the Canals if you are in the area.<//review>

1511868854962<//Time>
< text>
The canals are a pleasant area of tranquillity amid the hustle bustle of West Los Angeles. They have historic value, having been built in the 1920 when the coastal towns of Santa Monica and Venice were still mainly holiday resorts. Although little has remained of the architecture of that era, the layout of the place testifies to what Venice looked like back then.< /text>

<user_name>Traci</user_name><date>1450962855485<//date><Rate>5</Rate>< Review>
This is a must-visit when in the Venice Beach or Santa Monica area! You can both walk over the bridges connecting each street as well as on the pathways directly alongside the canal, affording you up-close views of the beautiful homes and their little boats. Despite receiving a ton of tourist traffic (I assume), residents were very friendly.</Review>

< rating>
5<//rating>
< text>
The Venice Canals are serene, beautiful, and a great place to take a nice walk. The majority of people walking the canals are tourists, but it's never busy, and everyone is respectful of the homes these walkways border. Be sure to walk over the quaint bridges - they make for great photo opps! Homeowners have water access, so you may see them out and about on the water. Parking is a bit difficult, but it's worth the search. Enjoy this quiet place to get away to!< /text>

Park in city lot on Venice Bvld. a few blocks north for $10, walk to the beach, enjoy the boardwalk, go to Hinano Cafe for burgers and beer, walk back through canals to your car, and then hit Abbot Kinney on your way home. <Text>I am so glad I came here. This is a perfect spot to bring a romantic date. It doesn't matter what season it is, you will still find it very beautiful here. Of course, spring and summer seasons are better because you get to see the greens and flowers.

<user_id>113182045060103105066<//user_id><review>I hardly give anything a 5 star but I am giving this place a 5.
Since the time i read about this place i wanted to go here and it turned out to be better than my expectations. It gives you a venice kind of a feel and its actually a small locality . Its not a tourist place or  something so its very less crowded. There are these small channels of water running betwee the houses and its pawed with pedestrian path all along. If you have a baby you can carry a stroller. Then there are these bridges which connect the two ends.. Its a beautiful place. The houses are very beautiful too. There is also a small park for kids to play.. I visited this place with my wife and kid and they too enjoyed it a lot. Hard to find such a peaceful place in LA. You have some parking on the street nearby.< /review>< Time>
1409523731440</Time>
